Text.string: Tyreen Calypso is a Siren, capable of draining or “leeching” the powers of any living thing. I wonder if she has trouble dating.
Oh, Pandora. You confusing mistress, you.
Do you have some business with me? If not, can you kindly get out of my grill?
If you have already forgotten my name, I am Patricia Tannis. An Eridian expert. I dislike... people—present company excluded. Or am I being nice?

I'm not surprised the Calypsos were able to trick the bandits into worshipping them as gods. Bandits don't seem to recognize scientific fact, like the Demner Trials, where it was definitively proven that God doesn't exist—and that bacon is proof that the devil does.
Lilith was part of the original team that opened the first Vault on Pandora. They defeated a monster known as the Destroyer, a name I have seen many times in my studies.
Why did the Eridians leave a map within a Vault Key? That is the question we should be asking.
I wonder if the Great Vault is real, and if so, how the Calypsos discovered it. I've read mention of a “Vault of Vaults”, but have never discovered more than the name.
If living by yourself in a scorched wasteland and researching a long-extinct alien species is wrong, I don't want to be right.
Eridian, Eridium, Eridian, Eridium—just warming up! Blithering idiot, blistering rebuke, blithering...
Typhon DeLeon has been alive all this time. Fascinating! On an unrelated note, what is the current mode du jour on contraception?
Nekrotafeyo is real. An Eridian homeworld. [sigh] I know the fate of Pandora is at stake, but I am very content right now.
Troy Calypso is dead, but Tyreen is out there somewhere—like a hangnail, just waiting to strike.
So... Ava is a Siren after all. I wonder how Maya knew.
Well, Troy Calypso is gone. I, for one, won't miss him in the slightest. He called me “weirdo scientist”, and I am clearly a preeminent weirdo scientist. Good riddance.
Ava saved our lives. She's a quick learner, that one. I'm almost ready to forgive her for stealing my surgical knives.
So, Typhon DeLeon is the father of Tyreen and Troy. I would surmise, then, that his wife Leda was a Siren.
The Eridians built a machine, a failsafe in case someone attempted to open Pandora by accident.
I don't blame DeLeon for how the Calypsos turned out. Pandora has a corrupting effect on all who set foot there. I proved this with my spore thesis.
Well, how are you holding up? That's a thing people say, is it not?
I will have to look into this Leda Calypso. Her name is... familiar. I might have crossed paths with her when I was a young researcher for the DAHL Corporation.
He's gone. And so my dreams of a house with a white picket fence, built on top of an Eridian temple, and a yard full of Guardians to dissect, comes to an end.
If Tyreen Calypso succeeds in leeching the Destroyer, she will technically become a god—for what is god but the most powerful being in the universe?

Pandora is breaking apart at the seams. Even if you manage some last-minute heroics and defeat both Tyreen and the Destroyer, there's still the problem of Elpis. That is one key that won't want to leave its hole!

This is it. The final showdown. The last, as they say, hurrah. If you do manage to save Pandora and thus the known universe, you'll have my thanks—though, as to what form aforementioned “thanks” will come in, I haven't decided.

I should have known Pandora was the Great Vault. As Typhon DeLeon once surmised—every craphole in this universe serves a purpose. If not to feed a future black hole, then to house the most powerful being in the universe. I'm paraphrasing, of course. Rest in peace, First Vault Hunter.
Lilith is gone. I won't pretend that I've shed any tears, though I will confess that my stray thoughts are filled with memories of her.
Well, you did it. You saved Pandora and the known universe. Though if history is any guide, it will be roughly two to seven years before another tyrant seeks the power of the Vaults.
I'm surprised to see you still aboard. I'd assumed you hero types took a break after saving the universe. I hear Junpai-7 is nice.
Well, did you get your fill of death-defying adventure? If not, I've got some adventurous erotic ECHObooks that you might like to peruse.
I don't think Lilith is gone. I've got no scientific backing to this, just a running hypothesis that the universe is not done with her yet. Hmm... I sounded like Maya at that moment. How odd.
I could go for some Digby Vermouth. My favorite album is Neon Dreamcicle.
Science cannot tell us everything. But it does separate humankind from beasts and music enthusiasts.

I am an Eridian expert, which means I know the most. But as it turns out, I know very little. The Eridians were a mischievous bunch who seemed to delight in dangling the fruit of knowledge in front of our face while releasing a monster behind us.
The difference between a scientist and a researcher is academic.
Yes? Do you have a query? Is this a poor attempt at flirtation, or have you gone blind?
Lilith is no longer a Siren.
Where is the Great Vault Key? I shall study this further.

Although I have never aspired to leadership, I must say I respect Lilith's forethought. This ship is incredibly well-equipped. But why it was just sitting in the middle of the desert is anyone's guess.
When you see Claptrap next, please let him know that none of my laboratory equipment has any interest in him romantically.
In all of my studies, I've never come across a mention of a male Siren. I wonder whether Troy Calypso even has powers. It seems to me that he is a Siren in tattoos only. How curious.
Ah, I see. You're seeking words of wisdom. Although I admire your curiosity, I have nothing for you at the moment.
As I said, Lilith is technically no longer a Siren, but she is still a leader. Those classifications are not mutually exclusive, I assure you.
Like, follow, and obey!||—What? It's catchy, I'll give them that.
I wonder why Troy Calypso seems to have no powers of his own. Perhaps his sister took his during adolescence.

Promethea was the site of the first Eridian Vault, opened by legendary Vault Hunter Typhon DeLeon. I arrived on Pandora shortly after DeLeon reportedly left on an expedition to the Eridian homeworld. He was never seen again.
I wonder where the Vault Map is right now.
It seems to me that the Calypsos already knew there was a Vault on Promethea.
Why did the Eridians trap monsters within the Vaults? Or perhaps the more curious question is, were they monsters when they went in?
If a Vault on Promethea exists, it is surely buried deep within the city. After Typhon DeLeon discovered the first Vault here, every corporation in the galaxy descended like locusts.
A Siren apprentice. How curious.
Maya says she has “faith” that Ava will become a Siren one day. But the girl has no tattoos. I'll wait for hard science on the matter before I pay it further attention.
The Calypso Twins claim that the Great Vault will make them gods. I suppose it's possible, if the Vault Monster within is big enough. After all, you are what you eat!
From what I gather of Athenas, it has something of a Siren tradition. Maybe it's something in the water.
Well, the Key is complete. Happy now?
I heard that you gave that Katagawa fellow's ass a proper kicking. Well done.
What are you waiting for? There is a Vault to open!
I must say I'm rather excited to see what we discover in this Vault.
Excuse me. I'm not quite ready for “human time”.
Do I smell bacon? Is that what all Vault Hunters smell like now? Or is that the collective odor of a grief-stricken crew?
Maya is gone. There is nothing more to say.

Tyreen Calypso is growing more powerful. And now that Troy has stolen Maya's abilities, I fear they are well on their way to dominating the galaxy. What? Do you come to me to feel better about yourself, or for dire prognostications?
I don't believe in an afterlife, but it hasn't been disproven. Where is Maya now? In our hearts? In the endless vacuum of anti-matter once deemed “dark heaven”? We may only speculate.
Well, one Vault down... it seems that the Great Vault does indeed beckon!
Eden-6. They say it's a paradise, but that term is a little suspicious, don't you think? One woman's beach is another woman's sunburn, after all.
The Jakobs Corporation. Probably like all the others. I worked for Dahl when I was a young researcher on Pandora.
Over the years, Sir Hammerlock has brought me many a rare specimen to experiment on. I'm glad you saved him.
Typhon DeLeon went to Eden-6 not long after he discovered the Vault on Promethea. Like you, he had a talent for sniffing out Eridian ruins and Key fragments.
A Jakobs resistance? Sounds exciting! But not to me.
I have research to do. If there is indeed a Great Vault, then it follows that there must be a Great Vault Key. But an artifact of that magnitude must be quite large! I shall consider it further.
When you're down there slumming it in paradise, keep an eye out for Typhon DeLeon's historical markers.
In my experience, betrayal is based on a desire for control. That is why I have excised all “friends” and made it clear to my archenemies that I am no longer interested in romantic encounters.
So, Troy Calypso sounds like a real... asshat is the term, I believe. Those who acquire power quickly usually go insane, or lead short but exciting lives, like pop musicians.

While you're out galavanting on the paradise of Eden-6, don't forget that the Calypsos are seeking the Great Vault, Ava lost her mentor, and Claptrap is wheeling around the ship proclaiming his ass's latest promotion. I am concerned.
Where did the Eridians go? Why do Vault Keys taste like sour apple? These are questions we may never have the answers to.
Ah, my rescuer! And now you know my secret. Or had you already guessed?
The Calypsos have already located the Great Vault. All that remains is to charge the Key, and then the Great Vault will open. I am concerned.
I acquired my powers from a Siren named Angel. The process was... complicated.
You must stop the Calypsos from opening the Great Vault. That is an order from your—oh, I'm only joking. I'm a researcher, not a commander.
So, you found the Vault Map. Kudos! Well done! Additional stock affirmations!||—Life is meaningless, you know.
Betrayed by Aurelia Hammerlock. In my experience, the very rich are the most miserable beings in the galaxy. They just don't know it.
So, you're a resistance fighter now, eh? How does it feel to be “one of the people”? Disgusting, I imagine.
A new ship AI. I'm intrigued. Lisps denote supreme intelligence, you know.
You find Vault Keys like pigs hunt truffles or robots collect oil-based bacteria. Well done!
There you are, my rescuer! Thanks again!
You acquired my Eridian amplifier. Well done.
So, Pandora is the Great Vault, Nekrotafeyo is real, and Typhon DeLeon is alive. My brain is about to explode like a thousand red giants—how about yours?
Having “fun” down there with DeLeon? Take me with you!
The Machine beckons. Not as catchy as the Great Vault, but it's true.
DeLeon is gone. You must stop Tyreen. That is all that matters now.
Well, we lost a Siren, but we gained a ship. I'm not sure of the arithmetic on that one, to be honest.
The hero approaches! Though “hero” IS a relative term, you know.
This bores me, as most things do.
Is this what you do for fun? Loiter?
I need to stay busy or my mind wanders. No one wants that, believe me.
Am I... waiting for something? I forget.
Mind if I practice my small talk? How is about this weather we're having? Please don't respond, I truly don't care.
Thank you for restoring my lab to operating condition. On an unrelated note, if you happen to spot an escaped, flesh-eating virus, please let me know.
I heard you won us some allies while on Promethea. Some people are like that, attracting friends and allies and well-wishers wherever they go. But I am not one of those types, and never will be.
I've always wanted to visit the Eridian ruins of Athenas, so I sincerely hope you were selective in how you applied your Vault Hunter brand destruction, yes?
You stopped a Vault-fragment-powered laser from destroying a city. I'd clap, but my hands are still covered in formaldehyde.
So, Atlas lives to see another day. That corporation brought death and destruction to Pandora during my Dahl researcher days. Well, slightly more death and destruction.
Maya is gone—but we opened the Vault. How does one usually reconcile these conflicting feelings of loss and loot?
Sir Hammerlock has brought me many a specimen over the years. I'm glad you saved him.
Busy? If not, please come see me.
Yoohoo, I have needs! Please fill them.
You there! Yes, you will do nicely.
Ah, hello Vault Hunter.
Hi, hello. Do you need something?
Salutations, Vault Hunter.
Yes?
Are you all right?
Toodles!
Ta ta for now.
This has been... Well, it's over now, so there's that.
Back to the lab!
How does one end a tedious conversation? Shoo now! Go on!
Until we meet again.
Run along now.
Later, brassiere! As Vaughn would say...
If you'll excuse me, I really should be doing absolutely anything else.
Leave me.
